<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-128-349 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 846 756</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  June 17 1991 n325 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Baby Bells get spanked: attractive alternatives are luringbusiness customers away from local telcos. (Bell Regional HoldingCompanies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Medina, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FCC is considering deregulating the $40 billion localtelephone market and opening it to competition.andP;  The seven BellRegional Holding Companies (BROCs), Bell Atlantic Corp, Ameritech,Pacific Telesis, BellSouth Corp, Nynex Corp, US West Inc andSouthwestern Bell are responding to the potential of competitionby reinforcing the loyalty of their customers.andP;  The BROCs alreadyare affected by some competition from alternative access carriers.andO;Ten percent of the local telephone market belongs to accesscarriers which provide better customer service and reliability aswell as lower prices.andP;  The BROCs have responded by lowering rates25 percent for services that parallel services offered by thealternative carriers.andP;  They also are entering joint ventures andpushing to obtain the right to manufacture equipment and provideinformation services.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesCompetitionUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionDeregulationCustomer relations.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Local telephone network alternatives in the top 20 cities. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>